{
  "doc_id": "47196",
  "text": "In the budding yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae, there is no ortholog of Taz1/TRF1/TRF2 and Rap1 directly binds the TG 1-3 telomere sequences [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Rap1 establishes a negative feedback loop on telomere elongation by telomerase [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] . For this pathway, Rap1 acts through its carboxy-terminal domain by recruiting two factors, Rif1 and Rif2, whose mode of action is still unknown [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] . Rap1 also establishes transcriptional silencing on the adjacent chromatin by recruiting a different set of factors through the same domain [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] . In addition, Rap1 binds the promoters of a large fraction of genes expressed during exponential growth, where it seems to play an essential role in transcriptional activation [CITATION_17] . Possibly because of its role in transcription, Rap1 is essential for viability in budding yeast, precluding the use of a simple gene knockout to study its functions [CITATION_18] .",
